    <h2 class="card-title">Tiny URL</h2>

<pre><code class="markdown">
# Requirement

Given an url, create a short version or simply return it if short version is already created
Length of URL of short version should be minimal
Can update existing URL to have different short version
Can delete existing URL

20 users, but grows
Each user make 1 write request and 10 read request per day, but grows
Size of each URL is estimated to be 100 bytes
Latency - 300ms

# High level

Long URL -> Service (->DB) -> Short URL

Workflow
- Service checks if short version already exists in DB
- If yes, return retrieved short URL 
- Else, compute short version, store it in DB, and return it

Service
- A single virtual machine
- Assume there is 64 chars to use to generate URLs
- Number of short URLs = 64**n where n is number of chars
- Assume 20 users grow to 1M, write QPS grows to 10 per day, and data retension is 5 years
- Then, we need to have 64**n > 1M * 10 * 365 * 5

DB
- A single SQL server

# API and Data

REST implementd by HTTP
- /api/v1/create_short_url(url) -> short_url
- /api/v1/update_short_url(url) -> short_rul
- /api/v1/delete_short_url(url) -> None

Data

Table - URL
- url_id (int, pk)
- url (string)
- short_url (string)

# Discussion

Performance
- Use cache in front of DB to handle read traffic fast
- Store frequently access data in key-value store
  - key: url
  - value: short_url
- Invalidate with TTL 
- Cache aside (if cache miss, read from DB and put it in DB, then return it)

Scalability
- Triggers
  - Server: >70% CPU, 80% memory, latency > SLA, number of connections > 10K/s
  - DB: read >5ms, throughput >10K write per second
  - Cache: >20% cache miss, read > 1ms
- Server
  - Add nodes (horizontal scaling)
- Cache/DB
  - Shard/partition data using shard key
  - Shard key is url_id
  - Consistent hashing to distribute shards across different nodes

Availability
- GLB to route incoming requests to nearest edge
- Servers, DB, Cache are deployed to each edge
- Active-Active where GLB healtchecks periodically on edge servers, and route traffic to live edges

Reliability
- Read path: in-memory cache -> Cache (Redis) -> DB. Three places to read data (can read data even if two of them fails) 
- When sharding, create replicas for each shard and spread replicas in nodes in different geo region

Consistency
- Strong consistency not needed (stale url is fine)
- Eventual consistency where data is consolidated later
- Sync: multiple requests to create/update the same URL
  - If single SQL DB, rely on built-in ACID
  - If distributed DB, use only one region for write relying on ACID and rest for read (slow write, SPOF)
</code></pre>

